Feature selection approaches

Feature selection can be defined as the process of reducing the number of input variables by identifying the relevant features and removing those irrelevant or redundant. The feature selection can improve the performance of machine learning algorithms, increase the learning speed, and simplify the model. Moreover, a smaller number of features lead to a reduction in instrumentation costs. Regarding the relationship between the selection algorithm and the learning algorithm, feature selection
Proposed feature selection method

Considering the limitations of the various feature selection approaches mentioned in Section 2, the proposed method for determining the best features used in identifying NPP transients is a hybrid method as shown in Fig. 4. As discussed in Section 1, the deep learning method is chosen for NPP transient identification. Unlike conventional neural networks, which are often composed of simple interconnected units, deep neural networks, as will be described in Section 3.2., have much more trainable
Training data set

The data set used to apply the feature selection methods and train the neural network for transient identification, has been generated by a compact full-scope simulator of a VVER-1000 nuclear power plant. The data set consists of 227 different scenarios that are classified into 7 groups based on the initiating events. The transients include anticipated operational occurrences (AOO), design basis accidents (DBA), and normal operation (NO) conditions. The use of data related to the normal
Conclusion

In the present study, a hybrid feature selection method was used to determine the most important parameters of an NPP for transient identification. In this method, several feature subsets are generated by calculating the score of each feature using several filters. The feature subsets are applied for training a deep LSTM network to determine a feature subset that leads to the best performance of the network in transient identification among the generated subsets.

